# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: actaeon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:actaeon/abas-mythology] In Greek mythology, the name **Abas** (/ă'-bas/; Ancient Greek: Ἄβας; gen.: Ἄβαντος, lit.
[src:actaeon/acantha] The tale supposedly goes that Acantha was a nymph loved by the god Apollo.
[src:actaeon/acantha] Acantha, however, rebuffed Apollo's continued advances and scratched his face.
[src:actaeon/acantha] As a result, Apollo transformed her into the Acanthus, a plant with spiny leaves.
[src:actaeon/acantha] The story has, over the years, been retold in books, encyclopedias, and journals.
[src:actaeon/acantha] Compilers have, however, often omitted reference to classical sources.
[src:actaeon/acantha] For instance, the first edition of John Lemprière's *Bibliotheca Classica*, an early encyclopaedia of mythological figures, provides no reference for the story.
[src:actaeon/acantha] In the updated 1839 edition three references are given.
[src:actaeon/acantha] These are to Pliny the Elder's *Natural History*, Pedanius Dioscorides' *De Materia Medica* and Hesychius of Alexandria's *Lexicon*.
[src:actaeon/acantha] On inspection, however, Pliny makes absolutely no reference to Acantha, Dioscorides refers only to the plant and Hesychius simply explains what the word means.
[src:actaeon/acantha] A number of latter compilers have similarly not cited classical references when retelling the myth.
[src:actaeon/acantha] The myth does not appear in the *Thesaurus Linguae Latinae*, a volume which includes every Latin word, including proper names.
[src:actaeon/acantha] The *Thesaurus Linguae Graecae*, a similarly comprehensive source containing a complete repository of Ancient Greek texts from Homer through to A.D.
[src:actaeon/acantha] The story is not present in either the *Lexicon Iconographicum Mythologiae Classicae*, a work praised for its breadth and quality, or *Der Neue Pauly*, an encyclopaedia considered an unparalleled masterpiece of classical German scholarship.
[src:actaeon/acantha] According to Cicero a woman named Acantho became the mother of the "fourth sun" in Rhodes.
[src:actaeon/acanthis-mythology] In Greek mythology, **Acanthis** (Ancient Greek: Ἀκανθίς means 'thornette') or **Acanthyllis** (Ἀκανθυλλίς) was the daughter of Hippodamia and Autonous and sister to Anthus, Erodius, Schoeneus and Acanthus.
[src:actaeon/acanthis-mythology] When their father's horses attacked Anthus out of hunger and ate him, Zeus and Apollo, out of pity for the grieving family, transformed them into birds.
[src:actaeon/acanthus-son-of-autonous] In Greek mythology, **Acanthus** (Ancient Greek: Ακανθος *Akanthos* means 'thorn') was the son of Autonous (son of Melaneus) and Hippodamia.
[src:actaeon/acanthus-son-of-autonous] He was the brother of Acanthis, Erodius, Anthus and Schoeneus.
[src:actaeon/acanthus-son-of-autonous] The bird he turned into has been identified as the siskin, the linnet, the blue tit or other birds, but with little certainty.
[src:actaeon/acanthus-son-of-autonous] Perhaps he is supposed to be the male of the bird his sister Acanthis turned into.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous was able to change his shape, and in the form of a bull, he wrestled Heracles for the right to marry Deianeira, but lost.
[src:actaeon/achelous] He was also involved in the legend of the Argive hero Alcmaeon.
[src:actaeon/achelous] The name Ἀχελώϊος is possibly pre-Greek; its meaning is not entirely certain.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Recent arguments suggest it is Semitic in origin, with the initial Αχ- stemming from the Akkadian *aḫu* ("bank of the river"), or *aḫû* ("seashore") and the suffix -ελώἴος, from the Akkadian *illu* ("watercourse" or "water of the river invading land").
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to linguist Ivan Duridanov, the Thracian river name *Achelōos* (alternatively, *Achēlon* and *Achelon*), located near Anchialo, in the Black Sea, is cognate to the Greek word, both deriving from a Proto-Indo-European stem **ɘku̯el*, meaning 'water'.
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to Hesiod, Achelous, along with all the other river gods, was the son of the Titans Oceanus and Tethys.
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to the sixth-century mythographer Acusilaus, Achelous was the "oldest and most honoured" of the river-god offspring of Oceanus.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Servius, relating a tradition of unknown origin, reports that Achelous was said to have been the son of Earth (i.e.
[src:actaeon/achelous] He was said to be the father of the Sirens.
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to the 3rd-century BC poet Lycophron, the Sirens were the daughters of Achelous, by an unnamed "melodious mother" (perhaps meaning the mother was a Muse), while Ovid calls the Sirens simply daughters of Achelous, with no mention of their mother.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Another 3rd-century BC, poet Apollonius of Rhodes, makes the mother the Muse Terpsichore, while according to other accounts, she was the Muse Melpomene, or the Calydonian princess Sterope.
[src:actaeon/achelous] By Perimede, the daughter of Aeolus, Achelous was said to have fathered Hippodamas and Orestes.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous was also said to be the father (with no mothers mentioned) of several nymphs associated with various famous springs.
[src:actaeon/achelous] These included Pirene, the nymph of a spring at Corinth, Castalia, the nymph of a spring at Delphi, and Dirce, the nymph of a spring (and the stream that flowed from it) at Thebes, which became associated with the Dirce who was Antiope's aunt.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Plato has "the nymphs" as daughters of Achelous, and the 5th-century BC poet Panyassis seems also to have referred to "Achelesian nymphs".
[src:actaeon/achelous] He was also the father (again with no mother mentioned) of Alcmeon's second wife Callirrhoe, whose name means "the lovely spring".
[src:actaeon/achelous] Such examples suggest the possibility of a tradition in which Achelous was considered to be the father of all springs or, at least, the nymphs associated with them.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous was a suitor for Deianeira, daughter of Oeneus, the king of Calydon; he transformed himself into a bull and fought Heracles for the right to marry Deianeira, but was defeated, and Heracles married Deianeira.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Sophocles, in his play *Women of Trachis* (c.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In later accounts, Achelous does not get his horn back, as he does in Pindar's poem.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Ovid, in his poem *Metamorphoses* (8 AD), has Achelous tell a different story.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In this version, Achelous fights Heracles, and loses three times: first in his normal (human?) shape, then as a snake, and finally as a bull.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Heracles tore off one of Achelous's bull-horns, and the Naiads filled the horn with fruit and flowers, transforming it into the "Horn of Plenty" (cornucopia).
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to the *Fabulae* (before 207 AD), by the Latin mythographer Hyginus, Heracles gave the broken-off horn to "the Hesperides (or Nymphs)", and it was "these goddesses" who "filled the horn with fruit and called it "Cornucopia".
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to Strabo, in some versions of the story Heracles gave Achelous's horn to Deianeira's father Oeneus as a wedding gift.
[src:actaeon/achelous] While several sources make Achelous the father, by various mothers, of the Sirens (see above), according to the 4th-century AD Greek teacher of rhetoric Libanius, they were born from the blood Achelous shed when Heracles broke off his horn.
[src:actaeon/achelous] The breaking off of Achelous' horn was rationalized as Heracles' diversion of the Acarnanian river.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Both Diodorus Siculus and Strabo give such accounts.
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to Diodorus, Heracles diverted the Achelous River's course, while according to Strabo, some writers "conjecturing the truth from the myths" said that, to please his father-in-law Oeneus, Heracles confined the river by means of "embankments and channels".
[src:actaeon/achelous] In this way, Heracles defeated the raging river, and in so doing created a large amount of new fertile land and "certain poets, as we are told, have made this deed into a myth" (Diodorus).
[src:actaeon/achelous] By both accounts, this new bountiful land of the Achelous River delta came to be known as Amaltheia's horn of plenty.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Joseph Fontenrose saw in this story the possible reflection of an ancient tradition of conflict between Zeus and Achelous.
[src:actaeon/achelous] For the Latin poets during the Roman Imperial period, from Propertius onward, the story of Heracles and Achelous' contest for Deianeria continued to be popular, with Achelous as "the stereotypical unlucky lover".
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous played a role in the story of the Argive hero Alcmaeon, who had killed his mother Eriphyle because of her treachery against his father Amphiaraus, and needed to be religiously purified.
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to Apollodorus, Alcmaeon was first purified by Phegeus the king of Psophis, but nevertheless the land of Psophis became barren because of the cursed Alcmaeon's presence.
[src:actaeon/achelous] As Thucydides tells the story, the oracle of Apollo told Alcmaeon that he needed to find a land to live in that did not yet exist at the time of his mother's death.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Later, according to Apollodorus, Achelous commanded Alcmaeon to dedicate the necklace and robe—the cause of his mother's treachery—at Delphi, which he did.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Ovid, in his *Metamorphoses*, has the river-god involved in two transformation stories concerning the creation of islands near the mouth of the Achelous River.
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to Ovid, the Echinades Islands were once five local nymphs.
[src:actaeon/achelous] One day, the nymphs were offering sacrifices to the gods on the banks of the Achelous, but they forgot to include Achelous himself.
[src:actaeon/achelous] The river-god became so angry, he overflowed his banks with a raging flood, sweeping the nymphs away into the sea.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous goes on to describe the creation of another island: "far away beyond the others is one island that I love: the sailors call it Perimele." She was the daughter of Hippodamas, whose virginity Achelous took from her.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Her enraged father threw her off a high cliff into the sea.
[src:actaeon/achelous] But Achelous prayed to Poseidon to save her, and in answer Poseidon transformed the girl into an island.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous's name could be used to refer to water in general.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In particular, his name was used to refer to the water that was mixed with wine for drinking.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Examples include three fragments from now lost fifth-century BC Attic plays.
[src:actaeon/achelous] A Sophocles fragment has the single line: "So Achelous runs with wine in our place", and a fragment from a satyr play by Achaeus has unhappy satyrs complaining about too much "of Achelous" being mixed with the wine they are being given to drink.
[src:actaeon/achelous] — Aristophanes; translation by Jeffrey Henderson.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Virgil has Liber (Dionysus) responsible for the mixing of the "draughts of Achelous" with wine.
[src:actaeon/achelous] While according to Hyginus, a man named Cerasus was the first to mix wine with "the Achelous river in Aetolia", explaining that this is why the word for "mixing" in Greek is *cerasai*.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous is also mythologically linked with Dionysus and wine, through his connection with Deianeira, and her father Oeneus.
[src:actaeon/achelous] There are various stories involving Oeneus (whose name means "Wine-man") Dionysus, and the origins of wine.
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to Apollodorus, Oeneus was the first mortal given the grape vine by Dionysus.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Hyginus explains that Oeneus was given the grape vine and instruction on viticulture by the wine-god, as a reward for his "generous hospitality" in having turned a blind eye to the god seducing his wife and fathering Deianeira.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Each is in the form of a cave, with four central figures, a male leading three nymphs, all holding hands gathered around a small stone altar (dancing?).
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous is represented as being carved into the cave wall (bottom left).
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous was a rural-agricultural water god whose importance was a reflection of the agricultural importance of rivers and their fertile river deltas.
[src:actaeon/achelous] This relationship is also reflected in the association of Achelous' broken-off horn with the cornucopia or horn of plenty.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Apparently some ancient Greeks considered sacrifices to Achelous to be even more important than those to the agriculture goddess Demeter.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Many inscriptions attest to the cult of Achelous, which was particularly associated with the oracle at Dodona.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Although of early importance, his cult declined in significance from the end of the fourth-century BC.
[src:actaeon/achelous] From at least as early as Homer, Achelous was apparently considered to be an important divinity throughout Greece.
[src:actaeon/achelous] The clear implication is that Achelous is the mightiest of the rivers (save perhaps for Oceanus himself), which would be in accord with Acusilaus' making Achelous the "oldest and most honoured" of the river-god offspring of Oceanus.
[src:actaeon/achelous] However some ancient scholars thought that the line: "nor the great might of deep-flowing Ocean", was spurious, which would in fact make Achelous—rather than Oceanus—the source of all other waters.
[src:actaeon/achelous] A commentary on *Iliad* 21.195, preserved on Oxyrhynchus Papyrus 221, contains a fragment of a poem, possibly from the Epic tradition, which mentions "the waters of silver-eddying Achelous" being the source of "the whole sea".
[src:actaeon/achelous] A late-5th-century BC commentary on an Orphic theogony, preserved by the Derveni Papyrus, quotes a poetic fragment calling the rivers the "sinews of Achelous".
[src:actaeon/achelous] The same Oxyrhynchus Papyrus also quotes ancient verses which apparently equated Achelous and Oceanus, and that "many people sacrifice to Achelois before sacrificing to Demeter, since Acheloios is the name of all rivers and the crop comes from water".
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous as a cultic figure is attested as early as the seventh century BC.
[src:actaeon/achelous] The 2nd-century geographer Pausanias, reports seeing, near Megara, an altar to Achelous erected by the seventh-century BC "tyrant", Theagenes of Megara.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous was the only river-god to achieve Panhellenic cult status.
[src:actaeon/achelous] By the fifth century BC he shared many sanctuaries with his daughters the nymphs.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous appears in many votive reliefs which often include nymphs.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Such reliefs were given as dedications in sanctuaries.
[src:actaeon/achelous] A votive relief (Athens 1488), dedicated to "Pan and the Nymphs", shows Hermes leading three nymphs in a cave, with a relief head of Achelous depicted on the wall of the cave.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In a similar votive relief (Athens 1859), Achelous is depicted as a bull with a human head.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous could also be venerated in the form of stylized votive masks, similar to the cult masks of the wine-god Dionysus.
[src:actaeon/achelous] A well-known example of such a cult mask, considered to be Achelous, is a marble mask (c.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Ephorus, explaining the "puzzle" of why Achelous name was used to mean water, said that, because of the frequent oracular command at Dodona to offer sacrifices to Achelous, it came to be thought that by "Achelous" the oracle meant, not the river but "water" in general.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Plato's *Phaedrus* has Socrates, walking in the countryside along the Ilissus river, come across a "sacred place of some nymphs and of Achelous, judging by the figurines and statues".
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous as a bull in the story of his contest with Heracles is part of a Greek tradition, perhaps as old as Homer (or older), of associating rivers and river-gods with bulls.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Strabo reports that according to some "the Acheloüs, like the other rivers, was called 'like a bull' from the roaring of its waters, and also from the bendings of its streams, which were called Horns".
[src:actaeon/achelous] This association is reflected in the fact that the Greeks depicted river-gods as part bull from at least the Archaic period onward.
[src:actaeon/achelous] There is also an ancient association between horns and the fertility that rivers provide, as can be seen in the story of the horn of plenty.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous was a popular subject in ancient Greek art.
[src:actaeon/achelous] There are many depictions of his fight with Heracles over Deianeira, with over twenty surviving examples in Attic vase painting alone.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous also appears in many votive reliefs along with other divinities often including nymphs.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous' man-bull iconography probably derived from oriental art.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Much more rarely, Achelous can also be found depicted in human form.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Besides Greek art, Achelous was also a common figure in Etruscan art.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous' contest with Heracles was the subject of many vase-paintings, from as early as the second quarter of the sixth century BC, and in most of these vases, Heracles can be seen grabbing Achelous by his single horn.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Possibly the earliest version of the scene (c.
[src:actaeon/achelous] 600–560 BC) appears on the figure frieze of a Middle Corinthian kylix cup (Brussels A1374), which depicts Heracles wrestling with a horned centaur-like Achelous, with a human torso and a bull's or horse's body, watched by the figure of an old man (Oineus?) and a woman (Deianeira?).
[src:actaeon/achelous] 570 BC) Attic versions (New York 59.64, Boston 99.519) depict Achelous as a bull with a man's head and beard.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Although many early depiction of this scene represent Achelous as a centaur, by the fifth century BC he is commonly represented as a bull with a human face.
[src:actaeon/achelous] 525–475 BC), an Attic red-figure stamnos from Cerveteri attributed to Oltos (British Museum E437), Achelous (identified by inscription) is shown with a bearded human upper torso, attached to a long serpentine body, with a fish's tail.
[src:actaeon/achelous] This is similar to the depictions of the sea-god Triton which appear on many other Attic vases.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Heracles (also identified by inscription) appears about to break off the river-god's single horn.
[src:actaeon/achelous] 475–425 BC) red-figure Attic column krater (Louvre G365), Achelous's broken-off horn lies on the ground, while Heracles holds Achelous by his other horn, and threatens him with a club held overhead.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Figures depicting Oineus and Deianeira (as on Louvre G365) and also Athena and Hermes are sometimes included in the scene.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Pausanias reports seeing the scene represented on the throne of Amyclae, and also in the Megarian Treasury at Olympia, where he describes seeing "small cedar-wood figures inlaid with gold" which, besides Achelous, included Zeus, Deianeira, Heracles, and Ares aiding Achelous.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Beginning in the late fifth century BC, Achelous also appears in many votive reliefs.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Such reliefs often include his daughters the nymphs.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Three marble Attic reliefs (Athens 1445, 1448, and 1859) have the form of a cave, with four central figures, a male leading three nymphs, all holding hands gathered around a small stone altar (dancing?).
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous, along with other figures, is represented as being carved into the cave wall.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In two of these (1448 and 1859, pictured above) the male central figure is Hermes, in the other he is Pan.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Votive reliefs without nymphs are also common.
[src:actaeon/achelous] A votive relief (Athens 1778), dedicated to Zeus and found near the Ilissos river, shows Zeus sitting on a stone seat decorated with the face of Achelous.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Although depictions of Achelous in the form of a man-bull in Heracles scenes and votive reliefs are very common, far more common are depictions of a man-bull unaccompanied by other figures.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In these contexts—where no inscription allows certain identification—the interpretation of such an individual man-bull as being Achelous is inferred.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In particular, depictions of a man-bull are found on the coins of many cites in Magna Graecia, Sicily, and elsewhere.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In addition to vase paintings, votive reliefs, and coins, man-bull depictions can also be found on many other kinds of artifacts, including gems, jewelry, bronzes, and architectural terracottas.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Although no single cult of Achelous persisted throughout all of these generations, the iconography and general *mythos* easily spread from one culture to another, and all examples of man-faced bulls are found around the area of the Mediterraneanan, suggesting some intercultural continuity.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Achelous was also an important deity in the Etruscan religion, intimately related to water as in the Greek tradition but also carrying significant chthonic associations.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Man-faced bull iconography was first adapted to represent Achelous by the Etruscans in the 8th century BC, and the Greeks later adopted this same tradition.
[src:actaeon/achelous] The leading exponents into the Greek and Etruscan worlds were seer-healers and mercenaries during the Iron Age, and Achelous as a man-faced bull becomes an emblem employed by mercenaries in the Greek world for centuries.
[src:actaeon/achelous] These earlier figures probably adapted the mythological and iconographic traditions of Asallúhi (also Asarlúhi or Asaruludu), the "princely bison" of Near Eastern traditions that "rises to the surface of the earth in springs and marshes, ultimately flowing as rivers".
[src:actaeon/achelous] The Achelous River rises in the Pindus mountains, flows into the Ionian Sea near the Echinades Islands in western Greece, and divided ancient Acarnania and Aetolia.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Servius gives a story of the origin of the river.
[src:actaeon/achelous] He says that one day Achelous, who was said to be the son of Earth, lost his daughters the Sirens, and in his grief he called upon his mother, who received him into her bosom, and on that spot, Earth caused a river, bearing his name, to gush forth.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Pseudo-Plutarch gives a different story for how the river acquired its name.
[src:actaeon/achelous] He says it was formerly called Thestius, after a son of Mars and Pisidice, who jumped into the river after discovering he had killed his son Calydon by mistake.
[src:actaeon/achelous] In a similar fashion the river acquired the name Achelous, after a son of Oceanus and the nymph Naïs, who jumped into the river after he discovered he had slept with his daughter Cletoria by mistake.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Strabo reports that in "earlier times" the river was called the Thoas.
[src:actaeon/achelous] According to Strabo, some writers "conjecturing the truth from the myths" attributed various legends concerning the river-god, to features of the Achelous River itself.
[src:actaeon/achelous] These writers said that, like other rivers, the Achelous was called "like a bull", because of the river's roaring waters and its meanders (which he says were called horns).
[src:actaeon/achelous] Likewise the Achelous was called "like a serpent" because of the river's great length and many serpentine turnings.
[src:actaeon/achelous] There were several other rivers with that name in ancient times.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Strabo mentions two other rivers named Achelous, one in Achaea near Dyme, also called the Peiros, the other in Thessaly near Lamia.
[src:actaeon/achelous] Pausanias mentions one more, a tributary of the Alpheius in the Peloponnese, near Mount Lycaeus in Arcadia.
[src:actaeon/achelous] The multiplicity of rivers with the same name, perhaps due to the river-god's equation with water, has also been seen as suggesting the possibility that Achelous was originally "the primal source of all water".
[src:actaeon/achelous] Ovid, in his *Metamorphoses*, provided a descriptive interlude when Theseus is the guest of Achelous, waiting for the river's raging flood to subside: "He entered the dark building, made of spongy pumice, and rough tuff.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The **Acheron** (/ˈækərən/ or /ˈækərɒn/; Ancient Greek: Ἀχέρων *Acheron* or Ἀχερούσιος *Acherousios*; Greek: Αχέροντας *Acherontas*) is a river in the Epirus region of northwest Greece.
[src:actaeon/acheron] In Greek mythology, Acheron is often depicted as the entrance to the Greek Underworld where souls must be ferried across by Charon (although some later sources, such as Roman poets, assign this role to the river Styx).
[src:actaeon/acheron] It is 52 km (32 mi) long, and has a drainage area of 705 km2 (272 sq mi).
[src:actaeon/acheron] The river's source is located near the village Zotiko, in the southwestern part of the Ioannina regional unit.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The Acheron flows into the Ionian Sea in Ammoudia, near Parga.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Ancient Greek mythology saw the Acheron, sometimes known as the "river of woe", as one of the five rivers of the Greek underworld.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Most classical accounts, including Pausanias (10.28) and later Dante's *Inferno* (3.78), portray the Acheron as the entrance to the Underworld and depict Charon ferrying the souls of the dead across it.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Ancient Greek literary sources such as Pindar, Aeschylus, Euripides, Plato, and Callimachus also place Charon on the Acheron.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Roman poets, including Propertius, Ovid, and Statius, name the river as the Styx, perhaps following the geography of Virgil's underworld in the *Aeneid,* where Charon is associated with both rivers.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The Homeric poems describe the Acheron as a river of Hades, into which Cocytus and Phlegethon both flowed.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The Roman poet Virgil called the Acheron the principal river of Tartarus, from which the Styx and the Cocytus both sprang.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The newly dead would be ferried across the Acheron by Charon in order to enter the Underworld.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The Suda describes the river as "a place of healing, not a place of punishment, cleansing and purging the sins of humans".
[src:actaeon/acheron] According to later traditions, Acheron had been a son of Helios and either Gaia or Demeter, who was turned into the Underworld river bearing his name after he refreshed the Titans with drink during their contest with Zeus.
[src:actaeon/acheron] By this myth, Acheron is also the father of Ascalaphus by either Orphne or Gorgyra.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The river called Acheron with the nearby ruins of the Necromanteion (oratory of the dead) is found near Parga on the mainland of Greece opposite Corfu.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Another branch of Acheron was believed to surface at the Acherusian cape (now Karadeniz Ereğli in Turkey) and was seen by the Argonauts according to Apollonius of Rhodes.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Greeks who settled in Italy identified the Acherusian lake into which Acheron flowed with Lake Avernus.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Plato in his *Phaedo* identified Acheron as the second greatest river in the world, excelled only by Oceanus.
[src:actaeon/acheron] He claimed that Acheron flowed in the opposite direction from Oceanus beneath the earth under desert places.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The word is also occasionally used as a synecdoche for Hades itself.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Virgil mentions Acheron with the other infernal rivers in his description of the underworld in Book VI of the *Aeneid*.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The Acheron was sometimes referred to as a lake or swamp in Greek literature, as in Aristophanes' *The Frogs* and Euripides' *Alcestis*.
[src:actaeon/acheron] In Dante's *Inferno*, the Acheron river forms the border of Hell.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Following Greek mythology, Charon ferries souls across this river to Hell.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Those who were neutral in life sit on the banks.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Acheron Lake in Antarctica is named after the mythical river.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Several English naval vessels have been named HMS *Acheron*.
[src:actaeon/acheron] There is a stream named the *Dry Acheron* in Canterbury, New Zealand.
[src:actaeon/acheron] The Eocene turtle genus *Acherontemys* of the Roslyn Formation in North America was named in reference to the Acheron mythos.
[src:actaeon/acheron] Acheron Fossae form large troughs north of Olympus Mons on the Mars northern hemisphere.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] In Greek mythology, **Actaeon** (/ækˈtiːən/; Ancient Greek: Ἀκταίων *Aktaiōn*) was the son of the priestly herdsman Aristaeus in Boeotia, and a famous Theban hero.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Through his mother Autonoë he was a member of the ruling House of Cadmus.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Like Achilles in a later generation, he was trained by the centaur Chiron.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Most depictions, both in ancient art and in Renaissance and post-Renaissance art, show either the moment of transgression and transformation, or his killing by his own hounds.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Among others, John Heath has observed, "The unalterable kernel of the tale was a hunter's transformation into a deer and his death in the jaws of his hunting dogs.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] But authors were free to suggest different motives for his death." In the version that was offered by the Hellenistic poet Callimachus, which has become the standard setting, Artemis was bathing in the woods when the hunter Actaeon stumbled across her, thus seeing her naked.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] He stopped and stared, amazed at her ravishing beauty.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Once seen, Artemis got revenge on Actaeon: she forbade him speech – if he tried to speak, he would be changed into a stag – for the unlucky profanation of her virginity's mystery.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Upon hearing the call of his hunting party, he cried out to them and immediately transformed.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] At this, he fled deep into the woods, and doing so he came upon a pond and, seeing his reflection, groaned.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] His own hounds then turned upon him and pursued him, not recognizing him.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] In an endeavour to save himself, he raised his eyes (and would have raised his arms, had he had them) toward Mount Olympus.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] The gods did not heed his desperation, and he was torn to pieces.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] An element of the earlier myth made Actaeon the familiar hunting companion of Artemis, no stranger.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] In an embroidered extension of the myth, the hounds were so upset with their master's death, that Chiron made a statue so lifelike that the hounds thought it was Actaeon.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Further sources, including the Hesiodic *Catalogue of Women* (from which only fragments survive) and at least four Attic tragedies, including a *Toxotides* of Aeschylus, have been lost.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Diodorus Siculus (4.81.4), in a variant of Actaeon's *hubris* that has been largely ignored, has it that Actaeon wanted to marry Artemis.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Other authors say the hounds were Artemis' own; some lost elaborations of the myth seem to have narrated their wanderings after his loss.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] A number of ancient Greek vases depicting the metamorphosis and death of Actaeon include the goddess Lyssa in the scene, infecting his dogs with rabies and setting them against him.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] According to the Latin version of the story told by the Roman poet Ovid having accidentally seen Diana (Artemis) on Mount Cithaeron while she was bathing, he was changed by her into a stag, and pursued and killed by his fifty hounds.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] This version also appears in Callimachus' Fifth Hymn, as a mythical parallel to the blinding of Tiresias after he sees Athena bathing.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] His reconstruction opposes a too-pat consensus that has an archaic Actaeon aspiring to Semele, a classical Actaeon boasting of his hunting prowess and a Hellenistic Actaeon glimpsing Artemis' bath.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] In the second century AD, the traveller Pausanias was shown a spring on the road in Attica leading to Plataea from Eleutherae, just beyond Megara "and a little farther on a rock.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] "As to Actæon there is a tradition at Orchomenus, that a spectre which sat on a stone injured their land.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] And when they consulted the oracle at Delphi, the god bade them bury in the ground whatever remains they could find of Actæon: he also bade them to make a brazen copy of the spectre and fasten it with iron to the stone.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Actaeon, torn apart by dogs incited by Artemis, finds another Near Eastern parallel in the Ugaritic hero Aqht, torn apart by eagles incited by Anath who wanted his hunting bow.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] The virginal Artemis of classical times is not directly comparable to Ishtar of the many lovers, but the mytheme of Artemis shooting Orion, was linked to her punishment of Actaeon by T.C.W.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Stinton; the Greek context of the mortal's reproach to the amorous goddess is translated to the episode of Anchises and Aphrodite.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Daphnis too was a herdsman loved by a goddess and punished by her: see Theocritus' First Idyll.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] In Greek Mythology, Actaeon is widely thought to symbolize ritual human sacrifice in attempt to please a God or Goddess: the dogs symbolize the sacrificers and Actaeon symbolizes the sacrifice.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Actaeon may symbolize human curiosity or irreverence.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] The myth is seen by Jungian psychologist Wolfgang Giegerich as a symbol of spiritual transformation and/or enlightenment.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Actaeon often symbolizes a cuckold, as when he is turned into a stag, he becomes "horned".
[src:actaeon/actaeon] This is alluded to in Shakespeare's *Merry Wives*, Robert Burton's *Anatomy of Melancholy*, and others.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] The two main scenes are Actaeon surprising Artemis/Diana, and his death.
[src:actaeon/actaeon] Some ancient authors, including Ovid, Hyginus, and Apollodorus, provide catalogues of the dogs' names.
